At this moment BIRT supports many data sources that read data from external source, e.g. JDBC data source, XML data source, flat file data source etc. If the user has custom requiremnts, he can use Scripted data source and provide data in any way (typically call some EJB). Nevertheless the user must be JS developer to do it.

Sometimes user wants to prototype some chart and he does not want to bother with preparing database schemas or flat files. Or user finds error in BIRT and wishes to submit small rptdesign without external dependencies. Or BIRT developer wishes to create test case. Then you can see such scripted data sources:

<method name="open"><![CDATA[i = 0;
sourcedata = new Array( new Array(2),new Array(2),new Array(2),new Array(2),new Array(2));
sourcedata[0][0] = "Keyboard";
sourcedata[0][1] = 320;

sourcedata[1][0] = "Mouse";
sourcedata[1][1] = 1700;

sourcedata[2][0] = "Memory";
sourcedata[2][1] = -387;

sourcedata[3][0] = "CPU";
sourcedata[3][1] = 890;

sourcedata[4][0] = "Cable";
sourcedata[4][1] = -790;]]></method>
<method name="fetch"><![CDATA[if ( i < 5 ){
row["Category"] = sourcedata[i][0];
row["SalesBalance"] = sourcedata[i][1];
i++;
return true;
}
return false;]]></method>

I think that you will agree with me, that 
a) write such data source is slow and tiresome
b) only developers are capable of writing it

So I propose to create new Tabular data source, where user can in WYSIWYG mode define table (number of columns, number of rows, column captions) including their row values. If the UI is designed well, it will speed up this use case by magnitude and it will help non-developers too.

Tabular data source

caption1   |  caption2  | [Add column] 
-----------+------------+-------------
value11    |  value12   | [Delete row]
value21    |  value22   | [Delete row]
value31    |  value32   | [Delete row]

[Add row]

There is a memory leak in MemoryBlocksTreeViewPane. The hash table of viewer states, fViewerState, accumulates references to IMemoryBlockRetrieval after they have been terminated.

TreeViewPaneContextListener.saveViewerState() is responsible for adding entries into fViewerState. It is called when the selection in the Debug view changes. 

The only method that removes items from fViewerState is ViewPaneEventHandler.doHandleDebugEvent(). It is called when a debug target is terminating. 

The leak occurs because the selection can, and often does, change after a launch has been terminated. For example, after the user terminates an active session, then launches another, the selection changes from an element in the terminated launch to one in the new launch. Because the selection has changed,  saveViewerState adds the retrieval object from the terminated launch to fViewerState, where it is never accessed again.

Now because the retrieval object is typically also the debug target (at least that's how we've implemented our debug model), an IDE can leak memory at a significant rate -- debug targets tending to be fairly heavy-weight objects that hold references to many other objects. Our users encounter noticeable degradation in performance after using our IDE for more than a couple days.

A partial fix to the problem can be made in doHandleDebugEvent() by setting fRetrieval to null after it has been terminated:

protected void doHandleDebugEvent(DebugEvent event) {
    // ... snipped ...

    if (event.getKind() == DebugEvent.TERMINATE)
    {
        // should only handle the terminate event if the target is terminated
        if (event.getSource() instanceof IDebugTarget)
        {
            IMemoryBlockRetrieval srcRetrieval =
                    getMemoryBlockRetrieval(event.getSource());
            if (srcRetrieval == fRetrieval)
            {
                 // #setInput must be done on the UI thread

                 // ... snipped ...							
                 job.setSystem(true);
                 job.schedule();
                 fRetrieval = null;  //     <------- add this line
            }

            IMemoryBlockRetrieval retrieval =
                    getMemoryBlockRetrieval(event.getSource());
            if (retrieval != null)
                fViewerState.remove(retrieval);
        }
    }
}

By setting fRetrieval to null when the debug target terminates, the subsequent call to saveViewerState() will skip adding it to fViewerState. This handles the most common case -- when the user terminates a session and starts another -- but doesn't handle the case where the user selects a terminated debug target, then selects an active one.

I'm not sure how to handle that case, since saveViewerState only has access to the retrieval object, which doesn't provide a direct path to a debug target. I suppose it would be possible to test whether the retrieval object is an IAdaptable and, if it is, request it's debug target adapter. Not bullet-proof, though. Maybe it doesn't need to be.

Using ASTRewrite, I am unable to set/remove static flag of import declaration correctly.

Example import declarations:
  import static org.eclipse.ClassA.A;
  import org.eclipse.ClassB.B;

I am trying to make second import static, first non-static using the following code:
  rewriter.set(importDeclaration1, ImportDeclaration.STATIC_PROPERTY, false, null);
  rewriter.set(importDeclaration2, ImportDeclaration.STATIC_PROPERTY, true, null);

The output after rewrite:
  import static org.eclipse.ClassA.A;
  static import org.eclipse.ClassB.B;

"static" keyword is not removed from first import declaration and is added incorrectly to the second import declaration. According to JLS 3, "static" keyword should follow "import" keyword (http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/third_edition/html/packages.html#26741).

Build id: M20060629-1905

I just experienced that after an renaming using refactoring a field variable a completly unrelated java dox @param changed too. What was special about @param was it had the same param name but was wrong compared to the method. Only "Opdate references" was set when I did the refactoring. e.i. in the below example I refactored class1's stdName to someOtherName - and it changed Class2 too - @param stdName changed to @param someOtherName. 


package a.b.c

public class Class1 {
    private final Object stdName = new Object();
}


package d.e.f

public class Class2 {
   /** Does nothing
   * @param stdName
   */
   public void method(int someOtherName) {
      return;
   }
}

JDT will mark the following use of "f" as an unnecessary local variable (which is right). However the named Quickfix will remove the line altogether (which is not right).

--- sample code, from JHotdraw 7.0.7 ---

public Figure basicRemoveChild(int index) {
...
}

public void basicRemoveAllChildren() {
    while (children.size() > 0) {
        Figure f = basicRemoveChild(children.size() - 1);
    }
}
--- what Eclipse does ---
public void basicRemoveAllChildren() {
    while (children.size() > 0) {
    }
}

-- what it should do ---
public void basicRemoveAllChildren() {
    while (children.size() > 0) {
        basicRemoveChild(children.size() - 1);
    }
}
